message.content:
We first calculate the Free Cash Flow (FCF) by adding the net cash flows from operating and investing activities. Then we compute the Current Assets Turnover Ratio as Total Revenue divided by the average of beginning and ending current assets.

Step 1. Free Cash Flow (FCF):
• Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –64,099.10 
• Net Cash Flow from Investing Activities = –528,936.17 
• FCF = –64,099.10 + (–528,936.17) = –593,035.27 

Step 2. Current Assets Turnover Ratio:
• From the balance sheet, Total Current Assets at the beginning is 8,000,000.00 and at the end is 9,717,259.46.
• Average Current Assets = (8,000,000.00 + 9,717,259.46) / 2 = 8,858,129.73 (approximately)
• Total Revenue (from income statement) = 5,064,939.23
• Current Assets Turnover Ratio = 5,064,939.23 / 8,858,129.73 ≈ 0.5715, which we round to 0.57

Thus, the answer in the required json format is:

{"solution": {"Free Cash Flow (FCF)": "-593035.27", "Current Assets Turnover Ratio": "0.57"}}
